<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-07-25T19:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-07-25T19:45:00-05:00" n="532" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d532">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5860: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-07-25T19:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">July 25,
                                        1928—7 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:50
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>295. General Feland reports that five aeroplanes returned today from
                            region described in Legation’s 292, July 21, 3 p.m., reporting <pb facs="0694" n="584" xml:id="pg_584"/> that they were again subjected
                            to machine gun and rifle fire, three aeroplanes being hit by rifle fire
                            but not seriously damaged. They returned the fire, but results not yet
                            reported and difficult to ascertain clue to dense forest. This occurred
                            at a lumber camp owned by a German citizen which the outlaws had seized
                            and were occupying.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>